{{refimprove|date=September 2013}} '''Dar-ul-Mussarat Lahore''' ('''DUML''') is a chain of [[special education]] centers for mentally challenged children in [[Lahore]], [[Punjab (Pakistan)|Punjab]], [[Pakistan]]. It was established in December 1990 by Khushnud Mussarat Azariah, wife of Bishop Samuel Robert Azariah.<ref name="ministry_of_diocese">{{cite web|url=http://dorcop.org/dar-ul-mussarat/ |title=Special Education |work=www.dorcop.org |accessdate=November 22, 2012 }}{{dead link|date=December 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>
The main campus of Dar-ul-Mussarat is in the Diocesan compound on Waris Road, along with St. Peter’s High School.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oxford.anglican.org/miscellaneous/interfaith/lahore-report.html |title=Lahore Report |work=oxford.anglican.org |accessdate=November 22, 2012 }}{{dead link|date=December 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>
Dar-ul-Musarrat Lahore is a daycare center for training and development of mentally challenged children. The main focus is to provide every opportunity to the handicapped children to be independent in their living activities. Under the supervision of Mrs. Resha Qadir Bakhsh (specially trained in Japan), the staff of 17 well-trained teachers help these children in developing awareness of their presence in this society. Dar-ul-Musarrat caters with the following disabilities: * [[Mental Retardation]] * Down's Syndrome * Cerebral Palsy * Autism Physiotherapy services are also provided
