{{use dmy dates|date=April 2015}} {{Use British English Oxford spelling|date=April 2015}} {{infobox person |name=Rebecca Root |image=Rebecca Root at the press conference of Sisters Brothers, 2018 Toronto Film Festival (44070760654).jpg |occupation=Actress, comedian, voice coach |website={{URL|rebeccaroot.co.uk}} |birth_date={{birth date and age|1969|5|10|df=yes}} |birth_place=[[Woking, Surrey]], England |residence=[[Highgate]], London, England |alma_mater=[[Royal Central School of Speech and Drama]] }}
'''Rebecca Root''' (born 10 May 1969) is a British [[actress]] and [[stand-up comedian]]. She was rated 18th in ''[[The Independent on Sunday]]''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s [[Rainbow List]] 2014, which named her as one of the very few openly [[transgender|trans]] actresses in mainstream television, alongside [[Laverne Cox]] and [[Adèle Anderson]].<ref name="IndRain2014"/> She played the leading role in the 2015–2016 [[BBC Two]] sitcom ''[[Boy Meets Girl (BBC TV series)|Boy Meets Girl]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b07k4tx0 |title=Boy Meets Girl |website=BBC online |accessdate=26 March 2018 }}</ref>
Root is also a voice coach,<ref name="GuardFightingMyself"/> teaching at the [[East 15 Acting School]] and from her home in [[Highgate]], London. She started that career after she [[transitioning (transgender)|transitioned]] and acting work became harder to find.<ref name="EnfInd"/> She graduated from the [[Royal Central School of Speech and Drama]] with a [[Master of Arts]] in Vocal Studies. Her thesis, "There and Back Again: Adventures in Genderland", has since been published in the peer reviewed journal ''Voice and Speech Review'', and she advertises voice therapy specifically for transgender people to help them "find a voice they feel fits their gender".<ref name="TeleVoice"/><ref name="RootBio"/><ref name="IndBBC2Commissions"/><ref name="Thesis"/>
In 2015 Root starred in the [[BBC Radio 4]] drama ''1977'',<ref name=bbcb06r8gms>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b06r8gms |title=Drama: 1977 |website=BBC online |date=3 December 2015 }}</ref> about the transgender popular composer [[Angela Morley]] who had become a household name to British radio audiences as Wally Stott. Written by Sarah Wooley,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sarahwooley.com/ |title=Sarah Wooley, writer for radio, TV, film, theatre |website=Wooley's website |accessdate=26 March 2018 }}</ref> it followed the year in which Morley was enlisted to complete composition of the musical soundtrack to the film [[Watership Down]] in three weeks flat.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/writersroom/entries/7c87da6e-c8b0-462e-86a9-b4227fdd25de |title=About so much more than 'a transgender woman in the 1970s' |website=BBC/blogs/writersroom |date=30 November 2015 }}</ref>
