In [[academic publishing]], a '''sister journal''' or '''companion journal''' is a newer [[academic journal]] that is affiliated with an older, better-established journal in the same field.<ref name=jmla>{{Cite journal |last=Akers |first=Katherine G. |date=2016-11-21 |title=New journals for publishing medical case reports |url=http://jmla.pitt.edu/ojs/jmla/article/view/62 |journal=Journal of the Medical Library Association |language=en |volume=104 |issue=2 |pages=146–149 |doi=10.5195/jmla.2016.62 |issn=1558-9439 |pmc=4816468 |pmid=27076803}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Bates |first=Susan E. |date=2017-02-01 |title=Too Many Journals |url=http://theoncologist.alphamedpress.org/content/22/2/126 |journal=The Oncologist |language=en |volume=22 |issue=2 |pages=126–128 |doi=10.1634/theoncologist.2017-0012 |issn=1083-7159 |pmc=5330714 |pmid=28188259}}</ref> ==Examples== *''JAAD Case Reports'' is a sister journal to the ''[[Journal of the American Academy of Dermatology]]'', both published by [[Elsevier]].<ref name=jmla/> *''[[Translational Psychiatry]]'' is a sister journal to ''[[Molecular Psychiatry]]''.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Licinio |first=J |date=April 2011 |title=Translational Psychiatry: leading the transition from the cesspool of devastation to a place where the grass is really greener |url=http://www.nature.com/articles/tp20113 |journal=Translational Psychiatry |language=En |volume=1 |issue=4 |pages=e1 |doi=10.1038/tp.2011.3 |issn=2158-3188 |pmc=3309469 |pmid=22832389}}</ref> *In 2001, [[BMJ Publishing Group]] launched ''[[BMJ USA]]'' and the ''[[Western Journal of Medicine]]'' as sister journals to ''[[the BMJ]]''.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Davis |first=Ronald M. |last2=Smith |first2=Richard |last3=Wilkes |first3=Michael |date=2001-02-17 |title=The US sisters of the BMJ: The BMJ is becoming more active in the US |url=https://www.bmj.com/content/322/7283/380 |journal=BMJ |language=en |volume=322 |issue=7283 |pages=380 |doi=10.1136/bmj.322.7283.380 |issn=0959-8138 |pmid=11179144|pmc=1119621 }}</ref> *''[[Science Translational Medicine]]'' is a sister journal to ''[[Science (journal)|Science]]''.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=McNutt |first=Marcia |date=2014-01-17 |title=Reproducibility |url=http://science.sciencemag.org/content/343/6168/229 |journal=Science |language=en |volume=343 |issue=6168 |pages=229 |doi=10.1126/science.1250475 |issn=0036-8075 |pmid=24436391}}</ref> *As of 1995, ''[[Nature (journal)|Nature]]''{{'s}} sister journals included ''[[Nature Medicine]]'', ''[[Nature Structural Biology]]'' and ''[[Nature Genetics]]''.<ref>{{Cite journal |date=April 1995 |title=Nature's sister journals in review |url=http://www.nature.com/articles/374577a0 |journal=Nature |language=En |volume=374 |issue=6522 |pages=577–578 |doi=10.1038/374577a0 |issn=0028-0836}}</ref> *''[[Oncogenesis (journal)|Oncogenesis]]'' is a sister journal to ''[[Oncogene (journal)|Oncogene]]''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nature.com/oncsis/authors-and-referees/authors |title=For Authors |website=Oncogenesis |language=en |access-date=2018-10-18}}</ref> *''STEM CELLS Translational Medicine'' is a sister journal to the [[Wiley-Blackwell]] journal ''STEM CELLS''.<ref>{{Cite journal |date=2015-01-22 |title=Editorial: Sibling Synergy |journal=Stem Cells |language=en |volume=33 |issue=2 |pages=316–317 |doi=10.1002/stem.1912 |pmid=25504305 |issn=1066-5099|last1=Lappin |first1=T. R. |author2=Editors of the Sister Journals }}</ref>
